Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women, the Polish Ministry of Justice said on Saturday.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said the treaty required schools to teach students about gender issues, violating the rights of parents.
Polish Justice Minister Giablo held a press conference saying that his Ministry of Justice on Monday would submit a request to the Ministry of Labour and Family to start withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
“The treaty contains elements of an ideological nature that we consider to be harmful,” says Joblo.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its governing coalition partners have close alliances with the Roman Catholic Church to promote a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Dudda made hostility to gay rights one of the main topics during this month's successful re-election campaign.
On Friday, thousands of Poles, most of them women, held protests against withdrawal from the Convention in Warsaw and a number of other cities.
One of the organizers of the protest, Lempat, said in a protest march in Warsaw that “the purpose of withdrawal from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence.”
Some protesters held banners saying “The Law and Justice Party is the hell of women”.
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's former central government ratified the Convention in 2015.
The Government of the Law and Justice Party stated that the treaty did not respect religion and called for liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
To date, however, the party has not decided to withdraw from the Convention.
