According to the FAA, four reports of aerial parking of the 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft engines have been received to date, resulting in urgent inspection requests for passenger aircraft that have been parked for 7 consecutive days or more, and for those with fewer than 11 flights to date after re-entry.
The FAA warns that the Class 5 check valves for all two engines of the passenger aircraft may get stuck in the open position if they are corroded, resulting in total loss of power and inability to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that, once the check valve is found to be corroded, the aviation operator must replace this critical component before the passenger aircraft is re-operational.
Boeing responded later that day, the coronavirus outbreak led to reduced travel demand, many passenger aircraft were sealed or less used, “check valves are more susceptible to corrosion.”
Boeing also said that air operators have been advised to check the aircraft involved in the instruction, and if it finds problems, Boeing will help with overhauling and replacing the check valve.
The Associated Press reported that the major US airline operators usually fly several times in a day, but after the COVID-19 outbreak, large numbers of passenger aircraft were grounded; as demand for passenger travel has recently grown slowly, some airliners are back into operation.
The FAA did not publish details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners from Seattle, Washington, D.C., to Austin, Texas on July 15, an engine suddenly went out, and the passenger plane finally landed in an emergency at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine of the passenger aircraft and had checked the engines of six airliners in accordance with the FAA directive.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th respectively that their aircraft did not have the engine flameout situation associated with the air check valve.
Four American Airliners will be inspected and 28 United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 airliners, but did not say if there had been an engine flameout.
