Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) - The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of Coco Sicily Management Office of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration Administration, Changjiangyuan Park Administration, the monitoring shows that the Tibetan antelope who had migrated to the Zhuonai Lake region in the heart of Coco Sicily is ending production of their children and began to return to their original children. habitat.
Surveillance pictures near the Wudaolang protection station show that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelope led three Tibetan antelope young children through the Qinghai-Tibet Highway 3002 km, the North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway Wudaoliang, and Tibetan Antelope has begun to relocate.
Experts analyze that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope young children in the relocated flock accounts for one-quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope flocks.
Lian Xinming, deputy researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: “Tibetan antelope faced a higher risk of predation, so the number of young children in the flock will be relatively small and may even have no young children.”
According to the Coco Sicily Management Office of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelope replacements has increased year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelope replacements was 4860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lian Xinming said: “The return of Tibetan antelope is expected to end in early September this year, and the number of relocations is expected to continue to increase.”
Tibetan antelope is a national protection animal.
At the end of May each year, Tibetan antelopes from Qinghai Sanjiang sources, Tibet Qiangtang, Xinjiang Alkin Mountain and other places go to Zhuonai Lake lambs in the hinterland of Kekesiri.
China's Tibetan antelope protection expert Wu Xiaomin, a researcher at the Shaanxi Institute of Animals (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: “The return of Tibetan antelope is the process of returning the female Tibetan antelope to their habitat after the end of birth. Initially, a large group of returnees leaving the land was larger, but the Tibetan antelope would then return to their respective habitats based on different geographical populations, along different paths.
