Is it reasonable to sue the school after 3 year old child's college playground play was smashed, after being compensated?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsibility Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, the child was compensated before the school.
□ The newspaper correspondent Zhao Yifan
The 3-year-old Xiaowen was accidentally hit by softball team Chen mu while playing in a college playground.
After Chen's compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as the legal representative of Xiaowen, brought the school to the court, asking the school where the incident was in place to apologize for compensation and pay medical expenses, mental damages, etc., a total of 20,000 yuan.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Beijing Haidian District People's Court held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and that Chen had already paid compensation, and that Chen had made compensation, and accordingly dismissed the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claimed that he took Xiao Wen to play at the school playground during the summer of 2019, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks, Mr. Xiao Wen, Man, and many other children and parents are active in safe areas designated by the softball team.
But then, softball team member Chen mu left his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly across the protective net to the above safe area and hitting the small man behind the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to hospital for treatment and was diagnosed as a head trauma.
Mr. Man believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not comply with the relevant safety requirements and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The negligence of the school has led to the events mentioned above, causing immense physical and psychological suffering to the small literary and psychological, and at the same time inflicting greater suffering on their families, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground and had posted regulations and training notices informing that access to the playground must be kept safe from the training site and reminded that it was safe, and that the plaintiff could not prove that the school had “failed to meet its safety obligations” and therefore did not agree to compensation.
After the hearing, the court held that the site of the incident was open to the public free of charge by the university and that although the school had an obligation to ensure the management of the playground, such a duty of safety was only required to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, and had already done its proper safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for damages such as medical expenses, transportation costs and other losses in accordance with the compensation agreement reached earlier. The two sides agreed to resolve the dispute at one time.
After the incident, Xiao Wen's parents once again argued for school compensation, and the court ruled out all the plaintiff's claims.
Since the judgement was delivered, neither party appealed, and the judgement is now in force.
According to article 37 of our law on tort liability, schools as administrators of public places have security obligations; in cases where the actions of third parties cause damage to others, the third party is liable for infringement, while the administrator of a public place who fails to meet the security obligations shall bear the corresponding additional liability.
According to the judge, as the administrator of a public place, it is most likely that the actual circumstances of the site as a whole, foresee the risks and damage that may occur, and thus to take the necessary measures to prevent or mitigate the extent of damage and the lowest cost of avoiding and mitigating damage, the law (b) The obligation to guarantee the exercise of social activities shall be imposed on them.
In the present case, the safety obligations of the school should be commensurate with the social activities carried out by the school in respect of unspecified entrants in the playground open to the public free of charge, in particular the adoption of basic safety measures and the obligation to inform about hidden risks.
In judicial practice, it is also not advisable to impose excessive security obligations on managers in public places.
If the school has adopted a protective net and has met its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and is not legally liable.
In addition, in the case of third party infringements, even if the administrator of public places such as schools fails to meet their obligations of safety and security, the liability is supplemented by damages, which, under the recently promulgated Civil Code, can be recovered from third parties.
Thus, in such incidents, the victim should not extend the scope of the claim after having received compensation from the direct infringer.
