Israel Strengthens Prevention and Control of Recurring Outbreaks
In the early days of the COVID-19 outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures have been effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures and the recent increase in the number of cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Israel, the Israeli government has taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic on several occasions.
On 28 February, the first case of COVID-19 was diagnosed in Israel, with the aim of quickly closing all ports of entry and exit, suspending non-essential trades, shifted schools into online teaching, restrictions on public transport and non-essential social activities, blockade cities with severe epidemics, joint military and police maintenance initiatives.
This series of measures quickly yielded positive results, and by mid-May, new confirmed cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) in Israel had dropped to single digits.
As the outbreak was brought under control, Israel's prevention and control measures were completely unsealed, and since June, the number of new cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) has gradually rebounded.
In particular, after entering July, the spread of the epidemic continues to accelerate.
In recent days, there are more than 1500 new daily cases in Israel for 8 days. As of July 25, the number of new cases reached 916.
As of 25 July, there were 59745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Faced with the rapid rebound, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On 6 July, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed public entertainment venues such as gymnasium, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs, and introduced a restricted public transport policy to limit the maximum number of passengers per bus to 20 passengers.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions including the implementation of “Fengcheng” on weekends, stipulating that the “Fengcheng” will be implemented every Friday from 17:00 to 5:00 on Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and periods, gymnasium, studios and other venues will be closed, restaurants and cafes are forbidden, and only takeaway services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli population has not paid enough attention to the severity of the outbreak and failed to join forces with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people went to the streets to protest over government measures affecting their own economic interests.
On 11 July, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
